<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 10; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
111 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FIRE ON THE MOUNTAIN: The Nature of Volcanoes photographs by Dorian Weisel, 
text by Carl Johnson (Chronicle: $18.95; 132 pp., paperback original). Volcanic 
eruptions rank among the most awesome natural phenomena. Carl Johnson's text 
includes clear explanations of the origins of volcanoes, the different types of 
lava (clinkery aa vs. viscous pahoehoe), etc. But Dorian Weisel's photographs 
give this book its appeal: Lava gushing like water in a fountain; cars and 
houses disappearing in a fiery rain of ash; molten rock exploding as it strikes 
cold seawater. The reader wonders how Weisel shot these dazzling pictures 
without being incinerated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
