<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE SLAVE IN THE EMPTY GRAVE by Raymond J. Libert (Dorrance: $6.95; 28 pp., 
paperback original). This slim novella describes the efforts of 16-year-old 
James to work his way across the South during the Depression. Stranded in 
Georgia, the industrious James makes a discovery that enables him to aid his 
benefactors, the last members of a family ruined by the Civil War. Libert 
writes agreeably, but this story belongs in an anthology of new writing, rather 
than in a book by itself. 
</P>
