<TEXT>
<P>
 ARGUING IMMIGRATION: The Debate Over the Changing Face of America edited by 
Nicolaus Mills (Touchstone: $12; 223 pp., paperback original). Collected from 
various mainstream publications, the essays in this anthology present moderate 
points of view in an increasingly acrimonious debate.The authors cite 
statistics on the contributions and costs of legal and illegal immigration, but 
rarely explain how the figures were calculated. The desire to appear both 
reasonable and politically correct forces the writers dance around the 
questions that make the issue a hot topic. Readers who hold strong views on 
immigration will find at least one piece that confirms their opinions; 
undecided readers will put the book down feeling like Omar Khayyam, who, after 
listening to "great argument," "came out by the same door as in I went." 
</P>
