<P>
MORE LUGGAGE LAMENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In response to "Luggage Lament," Louise Hauter's letter to the editor (Sept. 
26): I would much prefer to check everything -- but with luggage being lost and 
pilfered, it won't happen. I can handle the wait at baggage claim, though 
sometimes it seems forever.The business traveler can't or won't. No easy 
answer. 
</P>
<P>
 BETTIE T. ROMAN 
</P>
<P>
 West Hills 
</P>
<P>
 I've never had a fish fall on my head, but my luggage was placed in the 
lavatory for take-off and landing on an Air France flight to Paris. My bulkhead 
seat had no overhead compartment and there was no seat in front of me, under 
which to stow it, thus the potty treatment. 
</P>
<P>
 The carry-on fiasco is not tolerated on Lufthansa. There, carry-on luggage is 
inspected three times -- at the check-in counter, in the waiting area, and 
during boarding. Their rules of one bag per person and no garment bags, 
oversized-items or polo mallets (I've been hit by one -- thanks, TWA), etc., 
are strictly enforced.  
</P>
<P>
 AMI PORCELLA 
</P>
<P>
 San Luis Obispo 
</P>
