<HEADLINE>
<P>
WIDE-RANGING INTERESTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rodney Blonien is a former corrections official who is Sacramento's most 
active lobbyist on behalf of companies, cities and associations with interests 
in California's prison system. 
</P>
<P>
 He was second in command at the Youth and Adult Correctional Agency under Gov. 
George Deukmejian, leaving in 1987 to work for a law firm that represented Wall 
Street investment houses that underwrote bonds used to finance two California 
prisons. He now is affiliated with another law firm, and heads a small lobbying 
firm representing entities with interests in gambling, construction and 
prisons. Since 1989, his corrections clients have paid him more than $600,000. 
Among his clients are: 
</P>
<P>
 * Client: Wackenhut Corrections Corp. 
</P>
<P>
 Background: The Florida firm has a contract with the California Corrections 
Department to run a private low-security prison. 
</P>
<P>
 Payments, 1989-94: $220,260. 
</P>
<P>
 * Client: Assn. of California Construction Managers 
</P>
<P>
 Background: The group of firms manages construction of prisons. Blonien says 
his duties for this client extend beyond prisons. 
</P>
<P>
 Payments, 1989-94: $62,071 
</P>
<P>
 * Client: Fricot City Partnership 
</P>
<P>
 Background: The private group has tried to persuade corrections to locate a 
prison in this Mother Lode town. 
</P>
<P>
 Payments, 1991-94: $56,240 
</P>
<P>
 * Client: Eclectic Communications 
</P>
<P>
 Background: The firm has contracts with corrections to operate two 
low-security prisons and halfway houses. 
</P>
<P>
 Payments, 1991-93: $22,645 (no longer a client) 
</P>
<P>
 * Client: Walt Miller 
</P>
<P>
 Background: Developer in Hanford built apartments in cities where prisons were 
being built. 
</P>
<P>
 Payments, 1989: $11,473 (no longer a client) 
</P>
<P>
 * Client: Kitchell CEM 
</P>
<P>
 Background: The Sacramento subsidiary of a Phoenix firm has exclusive contract 
with corrections to oversee prison planning and construction program: 
</P>
<P>
 Payments, 1991-92: $2,321 City Business 
</P>
<P>
 Here are cities represented by Blonien that have prisons or contracts with 
corrections to operate "return-to-custody facilities" for low security-risk 
inmates: 
</P>
<P>
 * Folsom: Has two prisons. Blonien says his duties for this client extend 
beyond prisons. Payments, 1989-94: $183,931 
</P>
<P>
 * SB 1591 Cities: Association represents Shafter, Taft, Coalinga, Adelanto, 
Folsom and Delano, all of which operate return-to-custody facilities. Payments, 
1993-94: $44,857 
</P>
<P>
 * Shafter: Has a return-to-custody facility. Payments, 1992: $19,147 
</P>
<P>
 * Adelanto: Attempting to get a prison; has a return-to-custody facility. 
Payments, 1991-93: $15,130 
</P>
<P>
 * Soledad: Has one prison, second under construction. Payments, 1989-93: 
$11,110 
</P>
<P>
 * Corcoran: Has one prison and one is being planned. Payments, 1991-1992: 
$5,246 
</P>
<P>
 * Taft: Has a return-to-custody facility. Payments, 1989: $2,406 
</P>
<P>
 * Blythe: Has two prisons (no longer a client). Payments, 1991: $1,461 
</P>
