<HEADLINE>
<P>
DRUG SEARCHES AT SCHOOL UNNECESSARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Recently the (Newport-Mesa Unified School District) board for Corona del Mar 
High School and the Newport Beach Police Department came to an agreement on a 
very controversial issue. They have decided to allow police dogs to sniff 
students' lockers and vehicles at random times during the year.Being a 
sophomore at CDMHS, I think this is a bad idea. 
</P>
<P>
 I have attended CDMHS since eighth grade and have never seen or heard of 
students bringing drugs on campus. 
</P>
<P>
 A week ago my journalism class interviewed our principal, whose opinion was 
that our school has never had a problem with drugs. 
</P>
<P>
 So, if it's not broken, why fix it? 
</P>
<P>
 The principal's response was that the dogs provided a further deterrent to 
drug use. 
</P>
<P>
 I feel this program is unwarranted. It gives CDMHS a undeserved bad 
reputation. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite being one of the smallest schools in Southern California we are among 
the highest ranking scholastically and in sports. 
</P>
<P>
 Although this program will cost the school district nothing, it will tarnish 
our school's image. 
</P>
<P>
 JAMES STAUFFER, Newport Beach 
